.TH "SHAREDWORKER.SHAREDWORKER" "3JS" "January 22, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
SharedWorker.SharedWorker \- SharedWorker: SharedWorker() constructor
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This script passed to the \f[CR]url\f[R] element is
executed.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by having a Content Security Policy (CSP)
that restricts the locations from which scripts can be loaded, and by
always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings
and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations in the \f[CR]Worker()\f[R] constructor for
more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]SharedWorker()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates a
\f[CR]SharedWorker\f[R] object that executes the script at the specified
URL.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
new SharedWorker(url)
new SharedWorker(url, name)
new SharedWorker(url, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]url\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] object or a string representing the URL of
the script or module that the worker will execute.
This must be same\-origin with the caller\(cqs document, or a
\f[CR]blob:\f[R] or \f[CR]data:\f[R] URL.
The URL is resolved relative to the current HTML page\(cqs location.
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying an identifying name for the
\f[CR]SharedWorkerGlobalScope\f[R] representing the scope of the worker,
which is useful for creating new instances of the same
\f[CR]SharedWorker\f[R] and debugging.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing option properties that can set when creating the
object instance.
Available properties are as follows:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]type\f[R]
A string specifying the type of worker to create.
The value can be \f[CR]classic\f[R] or \f[CR]module\f[R].
The default used is \f[CR]classic\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]credentials\f[R]
A string specifying whether the browser sends credentials when importing
modules into a module worker.
The allowed values are the same as can be passed to the
\f[CR]fetch()\f[R] request: \f[CR]omit\f[R], \f[CR]same\-origin\f[R], or
\f[CR]include\f[R].
The default is \f[CR]same\-origin\f[R] (only include credentials for
same\-origin requests).
.RS
.PP
This is ignored for classic workers.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string specifying an identifying name for the
\f[CR]SharedWorkerGlobalScope\f[R] representing the scope of the worker,
which is mainly useful for debugging purposes.
.TP
\f[B]sameSiteCookies\f[R]
A string indicating which \f[CR]SameSite\f[R] cookies should be
available to the worker.
Can have one of the following two values:
.RS
.TP
`all'
\f[CR]SameSite=Strict\f[R], \f[CR]SameSite=Lax\f[R], and
\f[CR]SameSite=None\f[R] cookies will all be available to the worker.
This option is only supported in first\-party contexts, and is the
default in first\-party contexts.
.TP
`none'
Only \f[CR]SameSite=None\f[R] cookies will be available to the worker.
This option is supported in first\-party and third\-party contexts, and
is the default in third\-party contexts.
.RE
.RE
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]SecurityError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the document is not allowed to start workers, for example if
the URL has an invalid syntax or if the same\-origin policy is violated,
or if the \f[CR]sameSiteCookies\f[R] value is not supported in the given
context.
.TP
\f[B]NetworkError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the MIME type of the worker script is incorrect.
It should \f[I]always\f[R] be \f[CR]text/javascript\f[R] (for historical
reasons other JavaScript MIME types may be accepted).
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if \f[CR]url\f[R] cannot be parsed.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]url\f[R] parameter is a string when Trusted Types
are enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\f[CB]SharedWorker()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates a
\f[CR]SharedWorker\f[R] object that executes the classic script or
module at the specified URL.
.PP
The script must be same\-origin with the associated document, but may
itself import scripts or modules that are cross\-origin (if permitted by
CORS and other restrictions).
If a cross\-origin worker is required, users must load it from an
intermediate same\-origin worker or a blob.
.PP
For more information see Description in the \f[CR]Worker()\f[R]
constructor.
.SH EXAMPLES
For brevity, the following examples don\(cqt use Trusted Types.
In production your code should always use trusted types when passing
data originating from users into injection sinks.
.PP
For an example, see Using Trusted Types in the \f[CR]Worker()\f[R]
constructor examples.
.SS Basic usage
The following code snippet shows creation of a \f[CR]SharedWorker\f[R]
object using the \f[CR]SharedWorker()\f[R] constructor and subsequent
usage of the object:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myWorker = \f[B]new\f[R] SharedWorker(\(dqworker.js\(dq);

myWorker.port.start();

[first, second].forEach((input) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  input.onchange = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    myWorker.port.postMessage([first.value, second.value]);
    console.log(\(dqMessage posted to worker\(dq);
  };
});

myWorker.port.onmessage = (e) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  result1.textContent = e.data;
  console.log(\(dqMessage received from worker\(dq);
};
.EE
.PP
For a full example, see our \c
.UR https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/web-workers/simple-shared-worker
Basic shared worker example
